Hornady XTP bullets were designed for hunting, self-defense, and law enforcement. One of the great things about the XTP bullet is reliable performance, it features controlled expansion where six serrations divide the bullet into six symmetrical sections. These sections weaken the jacket to allow controlled expansion at low velocities and ensures fragmentation does not occur at high velocities. The XTP bullet is really known for its stopping power. They were designed from the beginning to expand reliably at a variety of handgun velocities and deliver deep, terminal penetration with every shot. Most handgun bullets are designed to perform at a single factory-specified velocity where the XTP bullet is designed to offer controlled expansion over a range of velocities.

Each XTP Bullet has a swaged core and drawn copper jacket to ensure uniform expansion and in-flight stability. Adding a cannelure to this bullet keeps the core and the jacket locked together while also allowing the cartridge case to tightly crimp, adding security at high velocities. This is not loaded ammunition.

postcontent:
This is a Yugoslavian M-57 / M57 Tokarev in 7.62x25mm.  The firearm is manufactured at the Zastava factory and imported by PW Arms of Redmond, Virginia.  

I have fired the weapon many times and found it to be a reliable, fire breathing, bullet launching, ammo chewing machine.  The recoil and firepower is somewhere between a .22LR and a Howitzer… But it’s closer to the Howitzer.  

I have cleaned the firearm after every range trip.  As the picture shows, I fire name brand factory loads through it.  The bore is clean and the grooves deep and prominent.  

The firearm comes with 3 magazines, the issued holster, the issued cleaning rod, and 1,300-rounds (sixteen 50-packs).  The image should nicely represent what comes with the pistol.  

This is the Mail Carrier of pistols – it’ll work in the rain, sleet, and snow. If you are looking for a sidearm with stopping power and durability consider this as a suitable choice.  It’s solid enough that if you manage to miss your target with all 1,300-rounds you can still flip it over and beat them with the thing.  

See the picture, think happy thoughts, don’t tell your wife, and contact me with an offer.  

Permit to Purchase or CC required along with an ID listing a Minnesota address.  I will fill out transfer paperwork.  This is for my own records and not intended to go anywhere else.

The magazine is made of high-strength polymer and is designed with grips for the spring on both sides making it simple to load. A 25- and 10-round version of the magazine is available. Both are proportionate in size to the centerfire version’s mag to maintain the authentic look of the 9mm MP5s magazine. 

The .22 caliber HK MP5 A5 operates on a blowback system. The bolt holds open when the magazine empties. Its front sight is adjustable for elevation and comes with interchangeable posts. The rear sight is adjustable for windage and elevation. Its safety switch rotates in the same manner as the 9 mm MP5.

title: For Sale:  Mosin Nagant Chinese Type 53 7.62x54r
location: Linn Creek ~ Camdenton Osage Beach area., Missouri, United States
postcontent:
I have a 1955.3 (Made in March of 1955) Mosin Nagant Type 53 bolt action military surplus rifle. Restored and in perfect working order. This is a CAI import as stamped on the receiver. It was about what you would expect for one of their guns. Beat to hell. I spent 3 hours removing cosmoline or what ever monkeys*** they used to store these. another 3 hours lightly sanding the surface. I removed just enough to reveal the CHU-wood (a very moisture resistant wood) and leave the 'battle scars'. I gave it  light stain and clear coat. Aesthetically, this is a stunning piece of history in my eyes. I have gone through the entire rifle and cleaned everything and finished with a light coat of oil. I have sent 100+ rounds through it with no problems of any kind and am laying 2 1/2" groups at 100 yards with just the rifle sights. It has a non removable folding bayonet. The weapon is tight, clean & shoots like the vet she is. 

I bought 2 T-53's the same day, same place from the same crate. The top one is what they looked like before. The bottom one is what you are buying. 

These are links to my photobucket album with pics.

http://i276.photobucket.com/albums/kk28/vintagedelights01/100_3389.jpg
http://i276.photobucket.com/albums/kk28/vintagedelights01/100_3383.jpg
http://i276.photobucket.com/albums/kk28/vintagedelights01/100_3386.jpg
http://i276.photobucket.com/albums/kk28/vintagedelights01/100_3384.jpg
http://i276.photobucket.com/albums/kk28/vintagedelights01/100_3385.jpg
http://i276.photobucket.com/albums/kk28/vintagedelights01/100_3388.jpg

No cleaning rod, like 99.99% of these you come across. A standard 30/06 rod works just fine.

In addition to the pics, here are a pair of videos of me shooting the rifle. One of the great draws to this carbine is some of the powder doesn't have time to burn off before it leaves the crown, resulting in the dragon fire...lol. I learned the hard way (first shots in the daylight video) that you MUST wear ear protection when using this beast. It is LOUD! Take this one to the range and people WILL notice.

When you come to pick it up, I live in a rural area so you will have the opportunity to shoot it that you like before you take it home. I stand behind my work. I am in NO way a gunsmith, just a Mosin enthusiast. A note on the ammo. This is military surplus and is DIRT cheap. a span can of 440 rounds only runs $99 online. (Seriously! Find any other 7.62 round in that .20 cents a round range & I'll eat one...lol) This is a hard hitting round that punches through 7/16" plate steel with the heavy ball. The light ball that i have shot tears the plate up pretty good too. 

FWIW, this round will take any animal on the North American continent and not think twice about it at all.

Me, standing. A friend with his SKS (NFS)
http://s276.photobucket.com/albums/kk28/vintagedelights01/?action=view&current=100_3362.mp4

Fireballs. 

http://s276.photobucket.com/albums/kk28/vintagedelights01/?action=view&current=100_3379_00.mp4

Call Dennis
REDACTED

If you fell my price is too high, I am open to offers. 

This posting is at 9:45PM on the 11th, I will be in St. Louis tomorrow afternoon/evening taking care of another trade. If you would like to meet then, it may be possible.

(With the increase in availability of both the MAGPUL PTS and MAGPUL USA parts, there has been some confusion regarding the differences between MAGPUL USA and MAGPUL PTS products. All MAGPUL USA and MAGPUL PTS products are made with DuPont polymer and either forged steel or aircraft grade T-6061 aluminum alloy, and are close to indestructible. Because of MAGPUL USA’s military contracts and the regulations regarding sales of US Made firearm parts (ITAR Restriction), MAGPUL USA products are generally not available for sale outside the United States, and are even restricted in several US states. MAGPUL PTS parts are contract manufactured by MAGPUL internationally and are legal for sale anywhere in the world. Additionally, some PTS parts are specifically designed for use on airsoft rifles (like the MIAD grips designed to house electric motors) but the CTR stock for sale here is designed to fit both real mil-spec buffer tubes , and the MBUS sights will go on any 20mm rail — .
